ce:section.ce:para:
Initially, we synthesized and characterized Hg2+-specific CDs and CdTe QDs as fluorescent probes. The transmission electron microscopy (TEM) and ultraviolet–visible (UV–vis) spectrometry were deployed (Fig. 1
                        ). The QDs have an average particle size of approximately 5 nm (Fig. 1a), and CDs, nearly spherical and dispersed, displayed a particle size of 4 nm (Fig. 1c). Upon introducing Ag+ and Hg2+, the Ag2Te was formed through a CER with QDs (Fig. 1b), while CDs aggregated with a thickness of about 20 nm (Fig. 1d). The UV–vis spectra of QDs exhibited an absorption peak at 540 nm (Fig. 1e), and that of CDs revealed two weak peaks near 408 and 670 nm (Fig. 1f). Ag was observed in energy dispersive X-ray spectroscopy (EDS) pattern of CdTe QDs after reacting with Ag+ (Fig. 1g and h), while Hg peak appeared in CDs' EDS pattern after reaction with Hg2+ (Fig. 1i and j). X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) was conducted to analyzed elemental composition and electronic states of materials. Ag3d binding energies was observed at 366.3 eV and 373.2 eV for CdTe QDs + Ag+ (Fig. 1k), while Hg4f binding energies at 99.4 and 103.4 eV for CDs + Hg2+ (Fig. 1l). Fourier transform infrared absorption spectra (FTIR) in QDs and QDs + Ag+ showed intensity decrease at 1720 cm−1 (C=O stretching vibration), with COO− and C–O stretching vibrations at 1570 (and 1400) cm−1 and 1070 cm−1 (Fig. 1m). The C–H, C=O, C–N, and C–O stretching vibrations were observed in CDs and CDs + Hg2+ (Fig. 1n). The intensity of photoluminescence (PL) characteristic peak at 550 nm decreased in QDs + Ag+ reaction, while Ag2Te was detected at the wave around 1200 nm (Fig. 1o and p) (Liu et al., 2021). The peak at 678 nm decreased significantly in CDs + Hg2+, while the characteristic peak of CDs at 470 nm was slightly affected (Fig. 1q and r), indicating specific interaction between Hg2+ and CDs (Zhao et al., 2017). Subsequently, Ag+/Hg2+, C–Ag+-C/T-Hg2+-T, and chol-C-Ag+-C/chol-T-Hg2+-T were designed to verify the extent to which the copolymer can increase the signal-to-noise ratio (Fig. 1s). The selective recognition of Ag+ over C–Ag+-C and Hg2+ over T-Hg2+-T was enabled with ions encapsulation. Then cholesterol-modified oligonucleotides aggregated into copolymers by annealing (Fig. 1t) (Liu et al., 2022). When introducing ions, the copolymers self-assembled into multi-armed hairpin structures, which increased the fluoresce signal and improved signal-to-noise ratio of QDs and CDs by 1.5 and 1.3 times, respectively. The phenomenon may be explained by enhanced steric hindrance within the polymer structure, remained the hairpin structures relatively stable, consistent with using biotin-streptavidin in the detecting system. Therefore, this design was expected to improve the performance and achieve high sensitivity in clinical detection (Scheme 1
                        ).
